author: @johnnyzhao7020
text: For the latest version of Jupyter, you need to rename 'sagemaker.s3_input' to 'sagemaker.inputs.TrainingInput' and it should work.  So it becomes: s3_input_train = sagemaker.inputs.TrainingInput(s3_data='s3://{}/{}/train'.format(bucket_name, prefix), content_type='csv')

author: @geekypratyush6485
text: Hi Krish and all the learners, just an update. For learners like me, who are trying to execute the above code in their jupyter instance, check the sagemaker instance first by command sagemaker.__version__. If it is "2.24.1", then sagemaker.s3_input won't work. Instead you need to write sagemaker.session.s3_input. Thanks for the video Krish.
